This legislation requires companies to regularly evaluate their tools for accuracy, fairness, bias, and discrimination. This is a key step toward ensuring more accountability from the entities using software to make decisions that can change lives. pic.twitter.com/tdk2iglHFP
We need a better understanding of what is happening with bias in algorithms and why. So Senator @RonWyden, @RepYvetteClarke, and I are introducing The Algorithmic Accountability Act today.

Research has shown that, due to algorithmic bias, well-meaning advertisers can unintentionally create discriminatory ads. And malicious advertisers can accurately target blacks, Latinos, women, the elderly, and LGBTQ members for exclusion from housing, employment and credit.

Sometimes this is due to intentional 1969-style ‚Äòsteering‚Äô online on social media platforms like Twitter, Facebook, etc. ‚Äì and the problems are bigger than simply removing discriminatory advertising categories.

The discrimination my family faced in 1969 is much harder to detect in 2019: houses that you never know are for sale, job opportunities that never present themselves, and financing that you never become aware of‚Äîall due to biased algorithms.

50 years ago my parents encountered blatant, in-person discrimination called ‚Äúreal estate steering‚Äù where black couples were steered away from certain neighborhoods in New Jersey. But with the help of local advocates and federal legislation they prevailed.

We need to talk about the fact that bias in algorithms is real and the possibility to exploit tech for the purpose of discrimination against vulnerable Americans is increasingly dangerous. https://twitter.com/mattoyeah/status/1116039811251560448¬†‚Ä¶
